segments.text: I had to go about the sprayers and everything.
Why don't you go ahead and tell me a little bit more about that and how y'all treated the boll weevil?
Well, that's about the... We didn't have very good luck with the boll weevils.
We still have the boll weevils.
You take the cotton region, but we live with them anyway.
And as the price of cattle went up, take for instance, I owned the gin and of course we didn't make, so got to where we didn't make too much cotton.
The gin went down, went out.
We just discontinued the gin and then we went into living of raising more livestock.
And as livestock had their ups and downs, the cattle prices would go down and go up as they do today.
We raised lots of turkeys in our community here.
Well, what did y'all do?
Take the turkeys to market and sell them?
We had a good market for turkeys.
There was a good market all over the state for turkeys.
And every farm home would have eight or nine turkey hens and raise eight or ten turkeys apiece.
And they'd eat grasshoppers.
They fed off of grasshoppers?
They fed off of grasshoppers.
I had ten turkey hens and I raised, I had a hundred turkeys, young turkeys and they just grazed around and eat the acorns from the trees in the fall of the year and they eat all the grasshoppers.
The grasshoppers were especially bad for the corn, you see, and they'd eat those grasshoppers.
Later on we began to go more into it as a commercial deal.
We, we
We went to feed those turkeys, and some places we sold turkey eggs for a dollar a piece.
I had a hundred turkey hens.
We had a big hatchery here in Bryan, a Casemore hatchery over there, and we sold them turkeys.
What did y'all feed the turkeys?
I mean, as feed, what did you use?
Grain, mixed feed, regular turkey feed.
There's a big market.
They put markets all over the state for turkeys.
They have those dressing places where they dress the young turkeys, kill them, and you could buy your Christmas turkeys.
It was a big business for a while, then it died down.
We went more into the cattle business later on.
Well, you mentioned, you know, y'all quit using the gin and everything.
Do you remember the purchase, the first purchase of new pieces of equipment, you know, like cultivators and stuff like that?
Can you remember the days that y'all...
I didn't buy no...
I bought... We used horses and mules at the time I was

first there and we had cultivators what we call walking cultivators and then later on they began to be mechanized and and they have the big tractors and things like that and they raised lots of land I mean raised lots of cotton and corn in the browser's bottoms and the creek bottoms.
Did the drought of, wasn't there a drought in 1925?
Yes.
That you said, did that affect your life greatly?
Oh yes, oh yes.
Well how'd y'all manage to get along then?
Well we, we, trouble was to have, we had a well and we used, drained by the barrel, used by the barrel of water and that's how we all would get that day until it seeped back in there.
You had to be pretty close.
We lost lots of cows.
Well, was there, when you were growing up, you know, as a young man, was there any motion picture shows around here?
No, no.
I don't remember any.
We got out when we were young folks and chunkwashed nests and went coon hunting and things like that.
When you, like you mentioned, going to parties and everything, what kind of games did y'all play, did you?
Well, we played those same old games we're playing today.
I don't know.
I ain't called a name to them.
Oh.
Go ahead and tell me a few.
Let's see.
I don't know.
Ring Around the Roses and Dr. Hankship and all those things.
And we had a game we played called Snap.
We didn't do so much dancing, but we did some dancing, too.
Then dancing came in.
What did this game, Snap, what did that involve?
Well, there was a boy and a girl holed up, and then the boy picked some girl to catch him and run around it, run around each other.
Oh.
Did you ever play that?
No, sir.
Did you ever hear it?
Where did you read it?
San Antonio.
San Antonio.
Wasn't there, in the county, wasn't there the old San Antonio Road is...
Yes, it's up above this county up here, the north end of the county.
The old San Antonio Road came through there.
Was that just a direct route from San Antonio?
It was a direct route through there.
The early settlers used King's Highway.
They called it the King's Highway.
How come?
Do you know why?
No, I don't know.
That's just the name they give it.
It's an old San Antonio Road and they call it the King's Highway.
Do you remember your father ever traveling on that, or did y'all do that?
Yeah, I traveled it later on.
I didn't travel it too early.
Not in my early days, I didn't travel it.
But it was a very much popular, a much used road at that time.
See, Texas was, you might say, in those early days, it wasn't settled.
Okay, well, did y'all, so then as vehicles, y'all used wagons and stuff like that?
Wagons and buggies.
Okay, well, what were some of the common problems with the wagons?
I mean, did y'all, like, did the wheels?
Well, the wheels, of course, we used wagons to raise, pull the cotton, and we used our soil piece in the paper.
Dave made me think, and I go back to that.
We used oxen, too.
We had oxen at that time.
And we had those oxen to use to pull cotton and to plow.
My, uh, my daddy had a fire yoga oxen down in the creek bottom where we are still on that land over there yet.
And they used those oxen to plow.
And that was mainly how y'all got into town and stuff?
It was... Well, we went there, we had buggies.
We went in buggies.
Oh.
Every family had a buggy and a horse.
And we'd go to town every Saturday, buy groceries.
Did y'all spend all day Saturday in town, usually?
Oh, not every day.
We'd just go there.
You had to go buy groceries and buy things and things, just like you do now.
Of course, now you can go there and come back in a few minutes, you see, and buy your groceries and car.
Well, can you remember, I mean, has the role of the woman changed very much?
The female, do you think, since, I mean?
I don't think.
too much.
They have been, well, they, yes, I don't want to get in the door as a woman to live.
Well, what was mine and their function?
I mean, were they?
They, they, they cared for the household, raised children, and raised the families.
Do you ever remember your mother attending any quilting days?
Yes, we had quilting parties.
They had quilting parties.
I gave a lady up the road here a pair of old quilting things the other day.
I found a pair I had in the shed.
They usually have quiltings and quilts.
My wife, during that Depression, I didn't mention that, during that Depression, the government gave cotton.
And she taught them how to make mattresses.
They'd give them cotton, bale after bale.
They had the cotton, you see.
And every family in this community, nearly all of them that wanted a mattress, which nearly all of them did, and some of them got three, they'd make a mattress.
And they could make those mattresses out of that cotton.
They knew how to do it.
They learned how to do it.
The government did that.
Oh, to help the... During the Depression, put it during that.
Okay, well you mentioned that your wife was working with the...
Yes, she helped in all the club work and she was a great worker with the club women of the county.
She was a member of the Harvey Community Club and they had this, they had the parties that meet once a week or something like that.
and have quilting bees, and have baby showers.

Well, somebody had mentioned to me that they used to hold a dance type thing where the men would all try to grow their beards up to a certain period, you know, and the ladies would come dressed in colonial dresses.
Do you remember anything about this?
Yeah, they did that for two years.
I didn't have a heavy beard like he's got.
So then for social, y'all just, social life, y'all just had parties and stuff like that?
Yes, we had our church and, well they had plenty of entertainment for people.
They were not hurt for entertainment.
Okay.
Do you remember...
Played ball, baseball, basketball, football, just like the dude did.
I got pictures of where I played football over at Sam Houston Normal.
Well do you remember anything like, were there ever any really what you would call saloons?
Saloon?
Yes.
I don't remember there was a saloon.
We had saloons here in Brown and of course there was quite a little bit of drinking but nothing.
Well, do you remember anything, I mean, like barroom brawls, like they would call them?
No, I don't remember that.
I'm kidding, I wouldn't think about it.
Which I know they had, all right, of course.
But Bryan was a very nice town, one of the quiet towns.
It was a college town.
We had A&M College over there, you see.
We always looked after A&M College, and A&M College has looked after us.
We've always spoke of Brown as being a city of schools.
We had the Allen Academy and several others.
We've had good high schools, good things like that.
Well, do you remember any certain thing that made the most impact on you?
Anything that happened while you were growing up here in Bryan, or anything that influenced you a whole lot, stands out in your life?
Well, one of the things that I said, we were busy making a living.
Everybody helped to make a living.
Every family raised chickens, hogs.
Had our own eggs.
We had our own garden.
and things like that.
So did you, as you farmed and was ranching and everything, did you have any tenant farmers?
Yes, I had.
One time I had six tenant farmers' families.
I had houses back over in the places over there.
They're torn down now.
I had six telephones.
Did you, do you ever recall your grandfather talking about slavery or anything?
Yes, he had no, I remember that very distinctly.
When they came in here, came to Texas, the old slave came with him.
And he stayed with him.
And he had slaves back in Alabama.
And
They loved the old slaves.
The slaves loved the master.
They didn't have no trouble with him.
Do you happen to recall this slave's name?
I'm just trying to think of that old slave's name.
I can't think of it.
Well, I think it's about run through.
I think I can ask you, can you think of anything that you might want to tell me right offhand?
I can think of anything you want to just... And I believe the government is trying to come back, come along the same way to try to help people.
They're reducing, they want to reduce taxes and
It would be a great benefit to people that need it, you see.
